</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[160,1156,1563,1727]" lastBlockId="28.[160,1156,142,582]" lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="893" pageId="27" pageNumber="892">
<bibRefCitation author="Kielland J" box="[160,323,1599,1623]" pageId="27" pageNumber="892" refId="ref22372" refString="Kielland J. 1990. Butterflies of Tanzania. Melbourne: Hill House." type="book" year="1990">Kielland (1990</bibRefCitation>
, p. 110) records 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Mabille" baseAuthorityYear="1876" box="[526,757,1599,1623]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Charaxes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="892" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="varanes" subSpecies="vologeses">
<emphasis box="[526,757,1599,1623]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="892">C. varanes vologeses</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from woodlands and open areas, thickets, and occasionally forests and montane forests, up to 
<quantity box="[904,994,1634,1658]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" pageId="27" pageNumber="892" unit="m" value="2300.0">2300 m</quantity>
<emphasis box="[1008,1021,1634,1658]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="892">–</emphasis>
apparently throughout 
<collectingCountry box="[300,399,1669,1693]" name="Tanzania" pageId="27" pageNumber="892">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
(mentioning the possibility of a separate subspecies on 
<collectingRegion box="[1064,1146,1669,1693]" country="Tanzania" name="Kusini Pemba" pageId="27" pageNumber="892">Pemba</collectingRegion>
). There does not appear to be any 
<collectingRegion box="[555,681,1703,1727]" country="Tanzania" name="Kilimanjaro" pageId="27" pageNumber="892">Kilimanjaro</collectingRegion>
area material of this common species in OUMNH, but the BMNH has a male collected 
<quantity box="[668,747,142,166]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.656064" pageId="28" pageNumber="893" unit="mi" value="6.0">6 miles</quantity>
northwest of Moshi, a pair from Old Moshi collected by Selous, and a pair from 
<collectingRegion box="[654,735,177,201]" country="Tanzania" name="Arusha" pageId="28" pageNumber="893">Arusha</collectingRegion>
, 
<quantity box="[746,827,177,201]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3716" pageId="28" pageNumber="893" unit="ft" value="4500.0">4500 ft</quantity>
, collected by Rydon. In 1982 the late Ivan Bampton observed 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Mabille" baseAuthorityYear="1876" box="[541,702,212,236]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Charaxes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="893" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="varanes" variety="vologeses">
<emphasis box="[541,702,212,236]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="893">C. v. vologeses</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
migrating in numbers, travelling up to 
<quantity box="[160,243,246,270]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.8" pageId="28" pageNumber="893" unit="km" value="480.0">480 km</quantity>
through central and northern 
<collectingCountry box="[588,687,246,270]" name="Tanzania" pageId="28" pageNumber="893">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Henning SF" box="[700,860,246,270]" pageId="28" pageNumber="893" refId="ref22224" refString="Henning SF. 1989. The Charaxinae Butterflies of Africa. Johannesburg: Aloe." type="book" year="1989">Henning 1989</bibRefCitation>
, p. 40; repeated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Larsen TB" pageId="28" pageNumber="893" refId="ref22516" refString="Larsen TB. 1996. The Butterflies of Kenya and their Natural History. 2 nd ed. Oxford (UK): Oxford University Press." type="book" year="1996">Larsen 1996</bibRefCitation>
, p. 282). On this basis it is included here as a member of the lower slopes fauna. While not encountered by 
<bibRefCitation author="Liseki SD" box="[482,626,316,340]" pageId="28" pageNumber="893" refId="ref22668" refString="Liseki SD 2009. Butterfly diversity and its relevance to conservation in north-eastern Tanzania [PhD thesis]. Canterbury (UK): University of Kent." type="book" year="2009">Liseki (2009)</bibRefCitation>
, evidently this butterfly has the potential to move into the lower levels of the main forest, and should be looked for. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Cramer, 1777)" baseAuthorityName="Cramer" baseAuthorityYear="1777" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Charaxes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="893" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varanes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="893">Charaxes varanes</emphasis>
(Cramer, 1777)
</taxonomicName>
, which occurs throughout almost the whole of Africa, is divided into three named subspecies: one occurs only in southern Arabia, the nominate 
<taxonomicName pageId="28" pageNumber="893" rank="subSpecies" subSpecies="occurs">race occurs</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[284,395,454,478]" name="Botswana" pageId="28" pageNumber="893">Botswana</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[413,560,454,478]" name="Mozambique" pageId="28" pageNumber="893">Mozambique</collectingCountry>
and most of 
<collectingCountry box="[742,890,454,478]" name="South Africa" pageId="28" pageNumber="893">South Africa</collectingCountry>
, while 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Mabille" baseAuthorityYear="1876" box="[983,1155,454,478]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Charaxes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="893" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="varanes" variety="vologeses">
<emphasis box="[983,1155,454,478]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="893">C. v. vologeses</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occupies a vast range, north to 
<collectingCountry box="[529,607,489,513]" name="Yemen" pageId="28" pageNumber="893">Yemen</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Henning SF" box="[623,786,489,513]" pageId="28" pageNumber="893" refId="ref22224" refString="Henning SF. 1989. The Charaxinae Butterflies of Africa. Johannesburg: Aloe." type="book" year="1989">Henning 1989</bibRefCitation>
, p. 36 
<emphasis box="[858,871,489,513]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="893">–</emphasis>
40; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ackery PR &amp; Smith CR &amp; Vane-Wright RI" box="[914,1120,489,513]" pageId="28" pageNumber="893" refId="ref20969" refString="Ackery PR, Smith CR, Vane-Wright RI, editors. 1995. Carcasson ' s African Butterflies: an annotated catalogue of the Papilionoidea and Hesperioidea of the Afrotropical Region. East Melbourne: CSIRO." type="book" year="1995">Ackery et al. 1995</bibRefCitation>
, p. 460). However, the Yemeni population appears distinct, and has since been named as a further subspecies (
<bibRefCitation author="Turlin B" box="[382,512,558,582]" pageId="28" pageNumber="893" pagination="171 - 182" refId="ref23919" refString="Turlin B. 1999. Observations sur les especes insulaires Africaines de la sous-famille des Charaxinae. Lambillionea. 99: 171 - 182." type="journal article" year="1999">Turlin 1999</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
